To read a file in Rust, you can use the `std::fs` module. Here's a basic example:

```rust
use std::fs;

fn main() -> std::io::Result<()> {
    let contents = fs::read_to_string("path/to/file.txt")?;
    println!("{}", contents);
    Ok(())
}
```

This reads the entire file as a string. For binary files or large files, consider using `fs::File` with a `BufReader`.

For async file reading in Rust, you can use the `tokio` crate:

```rust
use tokio::fs;

#[tokio::main]
async fn main() -> std::io::Result<()> {
    let contents = fs::read_to_string("path/to/file.txt").await?;
    println!("{}", contents);
    Ok(())
}
```

Make sure to add `tokio = { version = "1", features = ["fs", "rt-multi-thread", "macros"] }` to your Cargo.toml.
